6:
Aww... I had such high expectations for
that café's cake.
What a disappointment.
9:
Even Sir Alk is capable of baking
a more scrumptious tart.
13:
Argh... More importantly, how much
longer is this cretin going to
pursue me?
21:
This area looks suitable.
Come forward, fiend!
31:
That's my brother's technique!
Is it you, Ciel?!
34:
You identified me with a sword swing.
Well done.
36:
But, of course, I expected you to be this
capable. Or else, I wouldn't be here.
40:
But why now? It's almost time for you
to take over for father.
44:
We Tris are warriors. A man who runs
from battle is not fit to be its head.
47: So you wish to face me again.
49:
I thought your sword had broken...
But I suppose I was wrong.
56:
Another Enlil? Ciel... I can't believe it...
You defeated the dragon.
60: En garde! Demon Blade of Tris!
72:
It's just, all this talk of proving yourself
worthy to lead the Tris...
74:
And yet you seek to defeat me with
the techniques of other clans.
77:
You can decipher my blows that
quickly?
81:
The nine swords of Nouin. The dire
blade of Oinas. And a few more I don't
recognize.
83:
I see you have been traveling, Brother—
and it's done wonders for your
swordplay!
88:
Prepare yourself, Celtie!
Words will not finish our duel!
93:
Indeed! Let us settle this once
and for all!
99: Haha! Seems I've landed a blow!
102:
While I missed every strike I took...
I truly am no match for you, Cel.
107:
Don't feel bad. There's a reason
they call me a prodigy.
113: My! You been training this whole time?
116:
Indeed. I ventured out of the Farlands
and fought many formidable foes.
117:
I had thought to ignore Father's
summons and continue my travels.
But, alas, it seems I'll be a proud lord
as of next month.
119:
I needed to conclude things with you
before that.
124:
Please don't pity me, Cel. I feel relieved,
if you can believe it.
125:
Though, to be honest, I had every
intention of casting aside the sword
should I lose again.
127:
But now I think I want to carry on
regardless.
130:
Hehe. How fitting. For the true head
of Tris.
133: I see you've grown up a little.
140:
Before, you would swing your sword
like fire eating through wood—
consuming the art to reach greater
heights.
141:
You embodied the Tris style. Your blade
destroyed all that it touched, becoming
the object of father's fear... And
my envy. But no longer.
147:
I'm saying your swordplay has grown
disciplined, controlled. You must have
come across an excellent master.
150:
Hah, a master? If anything, it's quite
the opposite.
153:
Because I have found a student
in one Sir Alk!
156:
...No. It is obvious that you are the
one learning from him.
157:
By the way, if you plan to bring this
Alk back to the estate, do send word so
I can meet him before father.
161: I-I don't think of him like that!
164: I'll take my leave now, Cel.
166:
...Though, I hope we may duel
again soon.
170:
Of course. I'm always ready to cross
blades with you, Ciel!
183:
Nothing, it's just... I wanted to thank you
for everything. But don't get the wrong
idea!
194:
J-just don't get the wrong idea about
us! Well then, I'll be off now!
199:
Hold on, Celtie! Could we train together
today?
205: Yes! It would be my pleasure!
